# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: houdini-worklets
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:houdini-worklets/api-worklet] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:houdini-worklets/api-worklet] It’s been available across browsers since April 2021.
[src:houdini-worklets/api-worklet] The **`Worklet`** interface is a lightweight version of Web Workers and gives developers access to low-level parts of the rendering pipeline.
[src:houdini-worklets/api-worklet] With Worklets, you can run JavaScript and WebAssembly code to do graphics rendering or audio processing where high performance is required.
[src:houdini-worklets/api-worklet] Worklets allow static import of ECMAScript modules, if supported, using `import`.
[src:houdini-worklets/api-worklet] Dynamic import is disallowed by the specification — calling `import()` will throw.
[src:houdini-worklets/api-worklet] Worklets are restricted to specific use cases; they cannot be used for arbitrary computations like Web Workers.
[src:houdini-worklets/api-worklet] The `Worklet` interface abstracts properties and methods common to all kind of worklets, and cannot be created directly.
[src:houdini-worklets/api-worklet] For 3D rendering with WebGL, you don't use worklets.
[src:houdini-worklets/api-worklet] Instead, you write vertex shaders and fragment shaders using GLSL code, and those shaders will then run on the graphics card.
[src:houdini-worklets/api-worklet] Adds the script module at the given URL to the current worklet.
[src:houdini-worklets/audioworklet] The **`AudioWorklet`** interface of the Web Audio API is used to supply custom audio processing scripts that execute in a separate thread to provide very low latency audio processing.
[src:houdini-worklets/audioworklet] The worklet's code is run in the `AudioWorkletGlobalScope` global execution context, using a separate Web Audio thread which is shared by the worklet and other audio nodes.
[src:houdini-worklets/audioworklet] Access the audio context's instance of `AudioWorklet` through the `BaseAudioContext.audioWorklet` property.
[src:houdini-worklets/audioworklet] Returns a `MessagePort` for custom, asynchronous communication between code in the main thread and the global scope of an audio worklet.
[src:houdini-worklets/audioworklet] This allows for custom messages, such as sending and receiving control data or global settings.
[src:houdini-worklets/audioworklet] See `AudioWorkletNode` for complete examples of custom audio node creation.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Houdini is a set of low-level APIs that exposes parts of the CSS engine, giving developers the power to extend CSS by hooking into the styling and layout process of a browser's rendering engine.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Houdini is a group of APIs that give developers direct access to the CSS Object Model (CSSOM), enabling developers to write code the browser can parse as CSS, thereby creating new CSS features without waiting for them to be implemented natively in browsers.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Houdini enables faster parse times than using JavaScript `HTMLElement.style` for style changes.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Browsers parse the CSSOM — including layout, paint, and composite processes — before applying any style updates found in scripts.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] In addition, layout, paint, and composite processes are repeated for JavaScript style updates.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Houdini code doesn't wait for that first rendering cycle to be complete.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Rather, it is included in that first cycle — creating renderable, understandable styles.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Houdini provides an object-based API for working with CSS values in JavaScript.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Houdini's CSS Typed Object Model API is a CSS Object Model with types and methods, exposing values as JavaScript objects making for more intuitive CSS manipulation than previous string based `HTMLElement.style` manipulations.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Every element and style sheet rule has a style map which is accessible via its `StylePropertyMap`.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] A feature of CSS Houdini is the `Worklet`.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] With worklets, you can create modular CSS, requiring a single line of JavaScript to import configurable components: no pre-processors, post-processors or JavaScript frameworks needed.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] This added module contains `PaintWorkletGlobalScope.registerPaint` functions, which register completely configurable worklets.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] The CSS `paint()` function is an additional function supported by the `<image>` type.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] It takes parameters that include the name of the worklet, plus additional parameters needed by the worklet.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] The worklet also has access to the element's custom properties: they don't need to be passed as function arguments.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] In the following example the `paint()` function is passed a worklet called `my-component`.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Below you can find links to the main reference pages covering the APIs that fall under the Houdini umbrella, along with links to guides to help you if you need guidance in learning how to use them.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Defines an API for registering new CSS properties.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Properties registered using this API are provided with a parse syntax that defines a type, inheritance behavior, and an initial value.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Converting CSSOM value strings into meaningfully typed JavaScript representations and back can incur a significant performance overhead.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] The CSS Typed OM exposes CSS values as typed JavaScript objects to allow their performant manipulation.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Developed to improve the extensibility of CSS, the Painting API allows developers to write JavaScript functions that can draw directly into an element's background, border, or content via the `paint()` CSS function.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] An API for running scripts in various stages of the rendering pipeline independent of the main JavaScript execution environment.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Worklets are conceptually similar to Web Workers, and are called by and extend the rendering engine.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] Designed to improve the extensibility of CSS, this API enables developers to write their own layout algorithms, like masonry or line snapping.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] An API exposing the CSS parser more directly, for parsing arbitrary CSS-like languages into a mildly typed representation.
[src:houdini-worklets/houdini-apis] An API exposing font metrics, giving access to typographic layout results.
[src:houdini-worklets/sandbox-computer-security] In computer security, a **sandbox** is a security mechanism for separating running programs, usually in an effort to mitigate system failures and/or software vulnerabilities from spreading.
[src:houdini-worklets/sandbox-computer-security] The sandbox metaphor derives from the concept of a child's sandbox—a play area where children can build, destroy, and experiment without causing any real-world damage.
[src:houdini-worklets/sandbox-computer-security] It is often used to analyze untested or untrusted programs or code, possibly originating from unverified or untrusted third parties, suppliers, users or websites, without risking harm to the host machine or operating system.
[src:houdini-worklets/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox typically provides a tightly controlled set of resources for guest programs to run in, such as storage and memory scratch space.
[src:houdini-worklets/sandbox-computer-security] Network access, the ability to inspect the host system, or read from input devices are usually disallowed or heavily restricted.
[src:houdini-worklets/sandbox-computer-security] In the sense of providing a highly controlled environment, sandboxing can be comparable to virtualization.
[src:houdini-worklets/sandbox-computer-security] Sandboxing is frequently used to test unverified programs that may contain a virus or other malicious code without allowing the software to harm the host device.
[src:houdini-worklets/sandbox-computer-security] A sandbox is implemented by executing the software in a restricted operating system environment, thus controlling the resources (e.g. file descriptors, memory, file system space, etc.) that a process may use.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] In computer science, a **thread** of execution is the smallest sequence of programmed instructions that can be managed independently by a scheduler, which is typically a part of the operating system.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] In many cases, a thread is a component of a process.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] The multiple threads of a given process may be executed concurrently (via multithreading capabilities), sharing resources such as memory, while different processes do not share these resources.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] In particular, the threads of a process share its executable code and the values of its dynamically allocated variables and non-thread-local global variables at any given time.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] The implementation of threads and processes differs between operating systems.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Threads made an early appearance under the name of "tasks" in IBM's batch processing operating system, OS/360, in 1967.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] It provided users with three available configurations of the OS/360 control system, of which multiprogramming with a variable number of tasks (MVT) was one.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] The Mach implementation of threads was described in the summer of 1986.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] OS/2 1.0, released in 1987, supported threads.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Digital Research's MP/M operating system provided multiprogramming, multi-tasking, and preemptive multi-tasking for the Intel 8080 processor in 1979, and on the 8086 processor in 1981.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] The first version of Windows to have threads was Windows NT, which was released in 1993.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] In 1995, the IEEE defined the pthreads API, which standardized an interface for portable multithreaded programming across a variety of Unix-like operating systems.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Since then, pthreads has also been implemented on Windows with third-party packages such as *pthreads-w32*, which implements the standard on top of the existing Windows API.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] The use of threads in software applications became more common in the early 2000s as CPUs began to utilize multiple cores.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Applications wishing to take advantage of multiple cores for performance advantages were required to employ concurrency to utilize the multiple cores.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Scheduling can be done at the kernel level or user level, and multitasking can be done preemptively or cooperatively.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] This yields a variety of related concepts.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] At the kernel level, a *process* contains one or more *kernel threads*, which share the process's resources, such as memory and file handles – a process is a unit of resources, while a thread is a unit of scheduling and execution.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Kernel scheduling is typically uniformly done preemptively or, less commonly, cooperatively.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] At the user level a process such as a runtime system can itself schedule multiple threads of execution.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] If these do not share data, as in Erlang, they are usually analogously called processes, while if they share data they are usually called *(user) threads*, particularly if preemptively scheduled.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Cooperatively scheduled user threads are known as *fibers*; different processes may schedule user threads differently.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] User threads may be executed by kernel threads in various ways (one-to-one, many-to-one, many-to-many).
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] The term *light-weight process* variously refers to user threads or to kernel mechanisms for scheduling user threads onto kernel threads.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] A process is a heavyweight unit of kernel scheduling, as creating, destroying, and switching processes is relatively expensive.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Processes own resources allocated by the operating system.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Resources include memory (for both code and data), file handles, sockets, device handles, windows, and a process control block.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Processes are *isolated* by process isolation, and do not share address spaces or file resources except through explicit methods such as inheriting file handles or shared memory segments, or mapping the same file in a shared way – see Interprocess communication.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Creating or destroying a process is relatively expensive, as resources must be acquired or released.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] A *kernel thread* is a lightweight unit of kernel scheduling.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] At least one kernel thread exists within each process.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] If multiple kernel threads exist within a process, then they share the same memory and file resources.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Kernel threads are preemptively multitasked if the operating system's process scheduler is preemptive.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Kernel threads do not own resources except for a stack, a copy of the registers including the program counter, and thread-local storage (if any), and are thus relatively cheap to create and destroy.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Thread switching is also relatively cheap: it requires a context switch (saving and restoring registers and stack pointer), but does not change virtual memory and is thus cache-friendly (leaving TLB valid).
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] The kernel can assign one or more software threads to each core in a CPU (it being able to assign itself multiple software threads depending on its support for multithreading), and can swap out threads that get blocked.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] However, kernel threads take much longer than user threads to be swapped.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Threads are sometimes implemented in userspace libraries, thus called *user threads*.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] The kernel is unaware of them, so they are managed and scheduled in userspace.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Some implementations base their user threads on top of several kernel threads, to benefit from multi-processor machines (M:N model).
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] User threads as implemented by virtual machines are also called green threads.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Since scheduling occurs in userspace, the scheduling policy can be more easily tailored to the requirements of the program's workload.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] However, the use of blocking system calls in user threads (as opposed to kernel threads) can be problematic.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] If a user thread or a fiber performs a system call that blocks, the other user threads and fibers in the process are unable to run until the system call returns.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] A typical example of this problem is when performing I/O: most programs are written to perform I/O synchronously.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] When an I/O operation is initiated, a system call is made, and does not return until the I/O operation has been completed.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] In the intervening period, the entire process is "blocked" by the kernel and cannot run, which starves other user threads and fibers in the same process from executing.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Similar solutions can be provided for other blocking system calls.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Alternatively, the program can be written to avoid the use of synchronous I/O or other blocking system calls (in particular, using non-blocking I/O, including lambda continuations and/or async/await primitives).
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Fibers are an even lighter unit of scheduling which are cooperatively scheduled: a running fiber must explicitly *yield* to allow another fiber to run, which makes their implementation much easier than kernel or user threads.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] A fiber can be scheduled to run in any thread in the same process.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] This permits applications to gain performance improvements by managing scheduling themselves, instead of relying on the kernel scheduler (which may not be tuned for the application).
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Some research implementations of the OpenMP parallel programming model implement their tasks through fibers.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Closely related to fibers are coroutines, with the distinction being that coroutines are a language-level construct, while fibers are a system-level construct.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Operating systems schedule threads either preemptively or cooperatively.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Multi-user operating systems generally favor preemptive multithreading for its finer-grained control over execution time via context switching.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] However, preemptive scheduling may context-switch threads at moments unanticipated by programmers, thus causing lock convoy, priority inversion, or other side-effects.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] In contrast, cooperative multithreading relies on threads to relinquish control of execution, thus ensuring that threads run to completion.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] This can cause problems if a cooperatively-multitasked thread blocks by waiting on a resource or if it starves other threads by not yielding control of execution during intensive computation.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Until the early 2000s, most desktop computers had only one single-core CPU, with no support for hardware threads, although threads were still used on such computers because switching between threads was generally still quicker than full-process context switches.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] In 2002, Intel added support for simultaneous multithreading to the Pentium 4 processor, under the name *hyper-threading*; in 2005, they introduced the dual-core Pentium D processor and AMD introduced the dual-core Athlon 64 X2 processor.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Systems with a single processor generally implement multithreading by time slicing: the central processing unit (CPU) switches between different *software threads*.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] This context switching usually occurs frequently enough that users perceive the threads or tasks as running in parallel (for popular server/desktop operating systems, maximum time slice of a thread, when other threads are waiting, is often limited to 100–200ms).
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] On a multiprocessor or multi-core system, multiple threads can execute in parallel, with every processor or core executing a separate thread simultaneously; on a processor or core with *hardware threads*, separate software threads can also be executed concurrently by separate hardware threads.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Threads created by the user in a 1:1 correspondence with schedulable entities in the kernel are the simplest possible threading implementation.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] OS/2 and Win32 used this approach from the start, while on Linux the GNU C Library implements this approach (via the NPTL or older LinuxThreads).
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] This approach is also used by Solaris, NetBSD, FreeBSD, macOS, and iOS.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] An *M*:1 model implies that all application-level threads map to one kernel-level scheduled entity; the kernel has no knowledge of the application threads.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] With this approach, context switching can be done very quickly and, in addition, it can be implemented even on simple kernels which do not support threading.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] One of the major drawbacks, however, is that it cannot benefit from the hardware acceleration on multithreaded processors or multi-processor computers: there is never more than one thread being scheduled at the same time.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] For example: If one of the threads needs to execute an I/O request, the whole process is blocked and the threading advantage cannot be used.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] The GNU Portable Threads uses User-level threading, as does State Threads.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] SunOS 4.x implemented *light-weight processes* or LWPs.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] NetBSD 2.x+, and DragonFly BSD implement LWPs as kernel threads (1:1 model).
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] SunOS 5.2 through SunOS 5.8 as well as NetBSD 2 to NetBSD 4 implemented a two level model, multiplexing one or more user level threads on each kernel thread (M:N model).
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] SunOS 5.9 and later, as well as NetBSD 5 eliminated user threads support, returning to a 1:1 model.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] FreeBSD 6 supported both 1:1 and M:N, users could choose which one should be used with a given program using /etc/libmap.conf.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Starting with FreeBSD 7, the 1:1 became the default.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] FreeBSD 8 no longer supports the M:N model.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] In computer programming, *single-threading* is the processing of one instruction at a time.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] In the formal analysis of the variables' semantics and process state, the term *single threading* can be used differently to mean "backtracking within a single thread", which is common in the functional programming community.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Multithreading is mainly found in multitasking operating systems.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Multithreading is a widespread programming and execution model that allows multiple threads to exist within the context of one process.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] These threads share the process's resources, but are able to execute independently.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] The threaded programming model provides developers with a useful abstraction of concurrent execution.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Multithreading can also be applied to one process to enable parallel execution on a multiprocessing system.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Multithreading libraries tend to provide a function call to create a new thread, which takes a function as a parameter.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] A concurrent thread is then created which starts running the passed function and ends when the function returns.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] The thread libraries also offer data synchronization functions.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Threads in the same process share the same address space.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] This allows concurrently running code to couple tightly and conveniently exchange data without the overhead or complexity of an IPC.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] When shared between threads, however, even simple data structures become prone to race conditions if they require more than one CPU instruction to update: two threads may end up attempting to update the data structure at the same time and find it unexpectedly changing underfoot.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Bugs caused by race conditions can be very difficult to reproduce and isolate.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] To prevent this, threading application programming interfaces (APIs) offer synchronization primitives such as mutexes to lock data structures against concurrent access.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] On uniprocessor systems, a thread running into a locked mutex must sleep and hence trigger a context switch.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] On multi-processor systems, the thread may instead poll the mutex in a spinlock.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Both of these may sap performance and force processors in symmetric multiprocessing (SMP) systems to contend for the memory bus, especially if the granularity of the locking is too fine.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Other synchronization APIs include condition variables, critical sections, semaphores, and monitors.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] A popular programming pattern involving threads is that of thread pools where a set number of threads are created at startup that then wait for a task to be assigned.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] When a new task arrives, it wakes up, completes the task and goes back to waiting.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] This avoids the relatively expensive thread creation and destruction functions for every task performed and takes thread management out of the application developer's hand and leaves it to a library or the operating system that is better suited to optimize thread management.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] If all threads are busy, additional work items are placed in a queue until a thread becomes available to execute them.
[src:houdini-worklets/thread-computing] Many programming languages support threading in some capacity.
[src:houdini-worklets/worklet-addmodule] The **`addModule()`** method of the `Worklet` interface loads the module in the given JavaScript file and adds it to the current `Worklet`.
[src:houdini-worklets/worklet-addmodule] A `String` containing the URL of a JavaScript file with the module to add.
[src:houdini-worklets/worklet-addmodule] A `Request.credentials` value that indicates whether to send credentials (e.g., cookies and HTTP authentication) when loading the module.
[src:houdini-worklets/worklet-addmodule] A `Promise` that resolves once the module from the given URL has been added.
[src:houdini-worklets/worklet-addmodule] If `addModule()` fails, it rejects the promise, delivering one of the following errors to the rejection handler.
[src:houdini-worklets/worklet-addmodule] The specified script is invalid or could not be loaded.
[src:houdini-worklets/workletglobalscope] The **`WorkletGlobalScope`** interface is an abstract class that specific worklet scope classes inherit from.
[src:houdini-worklets/workletglobalscope] Each `WorkletGlobalScope` defines a new global environment.
